<div class="header"><h1>how are glutamate storms treated 2026-03-30</h1></div>
<div class="body">
<p>Glutamate storms (excitotoxicity) are treated by targeting excessive receptor activation, enhancing glutamate clearance, or providing neuroprotection to prevent cell death, often using medications like riluzole, memantine, or NMDA receptor antagonists. Treatment focuses on restoring the balance between GABA (inhibition) and glutamate (excitation) following acute injuries like stroke or TBI.<sup><a href="#fn1">1</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn2">2</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn3">3</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn4">4</a></sup></p>
<h2>Key Treatment Approaches: </h2>
<ul>
<li> Glutamate Receptor Antagonists: These block NMDA receptors to stop excess stimulation. Examples include memantine (for Alzheimer's) and amantadine (for Parkinson's), which reduce excessive glutamate-driven signaling.</li>
<li> Riluzole: An FDA-approved drug for ALS that inhibits glutamate release, enhances glutamate reuptake, and protects glial cells.</li>
<li> Blood Glutamate Scavengers: Experimental treatments like pyruvate and oxaloacetate act as "blood glutamate grabs" to reduce brain glutamate levels.</li>
<li> GABA Enhancers: Benzodiazepines are sometimes used to increase GABA, which acts as a counter-balance to reduce neuronal activity, especially in conditions with high anxiety or epilepsy.</li>
<li> Neuroprotective Agents: Vitamin C and N-acetylcysteine (NAC) have shown potential in reducing oxidative stress and supporting neuroprotection against excitotoxicity.</li>
<li> Nutritional/Metabolic Support: Maintaining blood sugar levels with IV glucose (dextrose) is essential in acute stages to provide energy for the brain's own glutamate removal mechanisms.<sup><a href="#fn1">1</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn3">3</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn4">4</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn5">5</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn6">6</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn7">7</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn8">8</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn9">9</a></sup></li>
</ul>
<h2>Alternative/Emerging Strategies: </h2>
<ul>
<li> Dietary Adjustment: Reducing dietary sources of free glutamate (e.g., MSG, processed foods).</li>
<li> Ketamine: Used in low doses to inhibit extra-synaptic NMDA receptors, showing promise in treatment-resistant depression by modulating glutamate systems.</li>
<li> Antibiotics: Ceftriaxone has been investigated for its ability to increase the expression of GLT-1, a transporter that removes glutamate from the synapse.<sup><a href="#fn10">10</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn11">11</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn12">12</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn13">13</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn14">14</a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Disclaimer: Glutamate storms are generally a secondary, often life-threatening consequence of a primary injury (e.g., stroke, head trauma) and require specialized, emergent medical care.<sup><a href="#fn15">15</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn16">16</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn17">17</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn18">18</a></sup>&nbsp;<sup><a href="#fn19">19</a></sup></p>

